<br>
EQ is a character progression based game.<br>
<br>
You progress thru leveling/aa, equipment and spells.<br>
<br>
All 4 of these methods are acquired through killing an NPC.<br>
<br>
Leveling/aa is achieved by killing many, many NPCs on a smaller scale (meaning they are plentiful in number and the duration for one to respawn, to attain the reward in the form of a sliver of exp that to suggest a rotation for an exp mob would require instant commital to the funny farm).<br>
<br>
Typically, items and spells are attained on a 'higher level' NPC or encounter.  Of course there are tradeskills, quests and spell research - but the norm today for character progression via items is to assemble a team (be it a guild or alliance) to defeat an NPC and obtain a reward.  These mobs have a much longer duration, thus character advancement (items) here takes much longer.<br>
<br>
Since ~1999, a group of competing guilds (bots/keg/ciw), after butting heads over and over concernign contested spawns -- sat down and ironed out a formal agreement to swap turns on mobs.  Through time, these ideas evolved and rules were set up, penalties were created, standards were formed.  As time elapsed many, many new guilds and alliances gained access to this swapping of turns on mobs, and the rotation system was formed and has existed nearly 4 years.<br>
<br>
Some of the fundamental rules consisted of time contsraints on how long you had for a mob, how many invites you could use (regarding planes), how alliances were handled and technicalities on entering the rotations.<br>
<br>
The principles of sharing these turns on mobs has many different points.  The standard for alliances was set:  when an alliance kills a mob, that alliance becomes an alliance throughout all rotational mobs that they can kill.  The logic behind this principally was that: it would be unfair for an alliance to team up on a particular mob, to defeat an NPC and recieve the reward(s) that progress the guild further, and then split off for various other mobs to defeat and gain separate instances of rewards from each.  Essentially, its about having your cake and eating it too, hehe...  To be given a fair shot at a mob, you must kill it alone for others to respect your turn.  If you use more than your guilds' powers, then you merge as a single entity.<br>
<br>
The ideal behind this was selfish for the parties involved.  They wanted to protect what was rightfully thiers by a defined agreement, and all agreed.  If you are capable of killing something, then all parties involved agreed to sacrifice a turn at that mob, and allow the other party to kill it, irregardless of who was ready first, or how badly you wanted to kill it.  It involved discipline, and patience and a bit of maturity.  <br>
<br>
But this sacrifice (of holding back from killing a mob, when you could -- but rather let a different team kill it) had the benefit of removing the stress and headache of racing to spawns.  which is why the rotational system has been successful (imo).<br>
<br>
The rotational system is more than fair.  It is 100% 'pro up-and-coming-guilds'.  There is no server elsewhere in eq, where guilds welcome others to migrate forward in progression in the game... none.  Guilds who could (and otherwise would) spawn camp mobs do not --because of the agreement and rules set up.  Guilds do not ally to kill a particular mob, then split off to kill others -- because this would severly stomp on the 'sharing' part of the rotational agreement, giving the 2 who teamed up an 'extra mob (or 2,3,4--however many other independent mobs they are rotating)' which would be 'taken' from all other parties involved.<br>
<br>
Moving forward, to PoP where a totaly new form of character advancement has been introduced to the game, in the form of flags.<br>
<br>
These flags, to me are like 72 loots per kill.  They are the textbook definition of character advancement.  Far more valuable than the mere 3-4 loots that drop off a mob.  To me, if a guild were to ally to kill a flag mob, and not maintain ally staus, it would be analagous to killing the AoW ~21 times under an alliance, while refusing to ally on other mobs - which by rules and definitions of the 4 year old agreement, are not allowed.<br>
<br>
I will clarify again, I have absolutely 100% no problem with any guild(s) teaming up to kill a flag mob in PoP.  I do however have a problem with the alliance trying to skirt the issue that they in fact, allied to advance thier characters to a level that they could otherwise not achieve -- which would be synonymous with allying to kill any other mob in the game that they could not kill alone-- which by precedent, would make them a formal alliance and merge all former rotations.<br>
<br>
It's about principles to me, which is where i drew my argument from in the first place.  It is inherently unfair to the actual formalities of the agreement (that states all parties will willingly NOT kill a mob that you are up for) if any party in the rotational agreement chooses to 'double up' to defeat a mob for progression -- one that they could otherwise not defeat on thier own.<br>
<br>
To me, it has no bearing that pop flag mobs are not rotated (in fact they are, only via Guildleader /tells).  It has to do with utilizing an artificial means to defeat something (via alliance) and then not accepting the responsibility of becoming a formal alliance across all rotational mobs you are involved with.<br>
<br>
